 by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. ap Idnerth was born about 1104, in Wales. She married Gwrgeneu Fychan ap Gwrgeneu ap idnerth in Wales. They were the parents of at least 5 sons."},"et":{"about 1104–":"umbes 1104–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","0972–Male":"0972–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","0972":"0972","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","about 1104":"umbes 1104","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","about 1130":"umbes 1130","about 1185":"umbes 1185","Wales":"Wales","of,,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1104–":"noin 1104–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","0972–Male":"0972–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","0972":"0972","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","about 1104":"noin 1104","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","about 1130":"noin 1130","about 1185":"noin 1185","Wales":"Wales","of,,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1104–":"environ 1104–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","0972–Male":"0972–Décédé","1130–Male":"1130–Décédé","1185–Male":"1185–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","0972":"0972","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","about 1104":"environ 1104","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","about 1130":"environ 1130","about 1185":"environ 1185","Wales":"Galles","of,,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. ap Idnerth est née environ 1104, à Galles. Elle a épousé Gwrgeneu Fychan ap Gwrgeneu ap idnerth à Gal